22 DACS LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICER JURISDICTION
23 SECTION 17. G.S. 106-900 reads as rewritten:
24 "§ 106-900. Powers of Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services law-enforcement
25 officers.
26 (a) Authorization to Appoint. – The Commissioner is authorized to appoint as many
27 Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services law enforcement officers as he or she deems
28 necessary to investigate and enforce any violation of the laws within the authority of the
29 Department or which occur on Department property. necessary. Such officers shall meet the
30 requirements of Article 1 of Chapter 17C of the General Statutes and shall take the oath of office
31 prescribed by Section 7 of Article VI of the North Carolina Constitution. Of these officers, the
32 Commissioner may designate certain officers to also have the powers and the duties of a forest
33 ranger enumerated in G.S. 106-898 and G.S. 106-899 and the power to enforce the forest laws.
34 A Department law enforcement officer may arrest, without warrant, any person or persons
35 committing any crime in the officer's presence or who such officer has probable cause for
36 believing has committed a crime in the officer's presence and bring such person or persons
37 forthwith before a district court or other officer having jurisdiction. Department law enforcement
38 officers shall also have authority to obtain and serve warrants including warrants for violation of
39 any duly promulgated rule of the Department.
40 (b) Territorial Jurisdiction. – A Department law enforcement officer is a State officer
41 with jurisdiction throughout the State, and beyond its boundaries to the extent provided by law,
42 in enforcing all matters within his or her respective subject matter jurisdiction as set forth in this
43 section.
44 (c) Subject Matter Jurisdiction. – After taking the oath described in subsection (a) of this
45 section, a Department law enforcement officer shall have the authority to arrest and take other
46 investigatory and enforcement actions for any criminal offense meeting any of the following
47 criteria:
48 (1) Occurring, encountered, or otherwise discovered on the premises of, or
49 elsewhere when the conduct relates to, property owned by, leased to, or
50 managed by the Department.
Page 10 Senate Bill 639-Fifth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (2) Provided for under this Chapter, including the forest laws as set forth in
2 G.S. 106-897.
3 (3) Provided for in any duly adopted rule of the Department.
4 (4) Encountered or otherwise discovered while investigating or enforcing matters
5 for the Department or encountered or otherwise discovered while
6 investigating or enforcing the provisions of this Chapter, including the forest
7 laws as set forth in G.S. 106-897 and any duly adopted rule of the Department.
8 (5) Encountered or otherwise discovered while carrying out any duty or function
9 assigned to the Department by law.
10 (6) Occurring in a Department law enforcement officer's presence.
11 (7) Occurring outside of a Department law enforcement officer's presence as
12 provided in G.S. 15A-401(b), and for other offenses evincing a flouting of
13 their authority as enforcement officers or constituting a threat to public peace
14 and order which would tend to subvert the authority of the State if ignored. In
15 particular, Department law enforcement officers are authorized to arrest for
16 violations of G.S. 14-223, 14-225, 14-269, and 14-277.
17 (8) When assisting another law enforcement agency.
18 (d) Authority. – Department law enforcement officers have authority as peace officers to
19 do all of the following:
20 (1) Execute criminal process.
21 (2) Obtain and serve warrants, including arrest warrants, search warrants, orders
22 for arrest, criminal summonses, citations, subpoenas, and warrants for
23 violation of any duly adopted rule of the Department, and all other process
24 connected with any cases within their subject matter jurisdiction.
25 (3) Respond to and take enforcement action for any crime of violence or breach
26 of the peace.
27 (4) Any additional duties as may from time to time be directed by the
28 Commissioner when needed for security purposes at a public event or to
29 protect persons or property because of a disaster or state of emergency.
30 (e) Primary Responsibilities. – The primary law enforcement responsibility of a
31 Department law enforcement officer is the enforcement of this Chapter, including the forest laws
32 as set forth in G.S. 106-897 and any duly adopted rule of the Department.
33 (f) Service of Orders. – Department law enforcement officers have the authority to serve
34 and execute notices, orders, or demands issued by the Commissioner, the Department, or the
35 Board of Agriculture relating to any administrative proceeding. While serving and executing such
36 notices, orders, or demands, Department law enforcement officers shall have all of the power and
37 authority possessed by law enforcement officers when executing an arrest warrant.
38 (g) Temporary Stops. – Department law enforcement officers are authorized to stop
39 temporarily any persons they reasonably believe to be engaging in any activity regulated by the
40 Department to determine whether the activity is being conducted in compliance with the law,
41 including license and permitting requirements. Department law enforcement officers are also
42 authorized to see that the provisions of Chapter 20 of the General Statutes are enforced within
43 their jurisdiction and shall have the power to arrest on sight or upon warrant any motor vehicle
44 upon the highways of the State for the purpose of determining whether the motor vehicle is being
45 operated in violation of any of the provisions of Chapter 20 of the General Statutes. If the person
46 stopped is in a motor vehicle being driven at the time and the Department law enforcement officer
47 is also in a motor vehicle, the Department law enforcement officer shall sound a siren or activate
48 a special light, bell, horn, or exhaust whistle approved for law enforcement vehicles under
49 G.S. 20-125(b)."
