1 INCREASE PENALTY FOR A SECOND OR SUBSEQUENT OFFENSE FOR
2 LARCENY OF CROPS AND FOR ROBBING OR INJURING AQUACULTURE
3 OPERATIONS
4 SECTION 18.(a) G.S. 14-78 reads as rewritten:
5 "§ 14-78. Larceny of ungathered crops.
6 (a) If It is unlawful for any person shall to steal or feloniously take and carry away any
7 maize, corn, wheat, rice or other grain, or any cotton, tobacco, potatoes, peanuts, pulse, fruit,
8 vegetable or other product cultivated for food or market, growing, standing or remaining
9 ungathered in any field or ground, that person is guilty of a Class H felony.ground.
10 (b) A violation of this section is punishable as follows:
11 (1) For a first offense under this section, the person is guilty of a Class H felony,
12 punishable by a fine of not less than two hundred fifty dollars ($250.00) in
13 addition to any other punishment prescribed for the offense.
14 (2) For a second or subsequent offense under this section, the person is guilty of
15 a Class G felony, punishable by a fine of not less than five hundred dollars
16 ($500.00) in addition to any other punishment prescribed for the offense."
17 SECTION 18.(b) G.S. 113-218 reads as rewritten:
18 "§ 113-218. Protection of private marine aquaculture rights.
19 (a) Offense. – It is unlawful for any person, other than the holder of a lease issued under
20 this Article, to take or attempt to take marine species being produced under the license and
21 associated lease from any privately leased, franchised, or deeded marine aquaculture operation
22 without written authorization of the holder and with actual knowledge it is a marine aquaculture
23 leased area. The written authorization shall include the lease number or deed reference, name and
24 address of authorized person, date of issuance, and date of expiration, and it must be signed by
25 the holder of the marine aquaculture rights. Actual knowledge will be presumed when the marine
26 species are taken or attempted to be taken under either of the following circumstances:
27 (1) From within the confines of posted boundaries of the area as identified by
28 signs, whether the whole or any part of the area is posted; orposted.
29 Identification signs shall include the lease number or deed reference and the
30 name of the holder.
31 (2) When the area has been regularly posted and identified and the person knew
32 the area to be the subject of private marine aquaculture rights.
33 (b) Penalty. – A violation of this subsection section shall be punishable as follows:
34 (1) For a first offense, the person is guilty of a Class H felony, punishable by a
35 fine of not less than two hundred fifty dollars ($250.00) in addition to any
36 other punishment prescribed for the offense.
37 (2) For a second or subsequent offense, the person is guilty of a Class G felony,
38 punishable by a fine of not less than five hundred dollars ($500.00) in addition
39 to any other punishment prescribed for the offense.
40 shall constitute a Class A1 misdemeanor, which may include a fine of not more than five
41 thousand dollars ($5,000). The written authorization shall include the lease number or deed
42 reference, name and address of authorized person, date of issuance, and date of expiration, and it
43 must be signed by the holder of the marine aquaculture rights. Identification signs shall include
44 the lease number or deed reference and the name of the holder."
45 SECTION 18.(c) G.S. 113-269 reads as rewritten:
46 "§ 113-269. Robbing or injuring hatcheries and other aquaculture operations.
47 (a) The definitions established in G.S. 106-758 are incorporated by reference into this
48 section. For the purposes of this section, a shellfish lease issued pursuant to G.S. 113-202 is
49 defined as an aquaculture facility only when it has been amended pursuant to G.S. 113-202.1 to
50 authorize use of the water column and when it is or has been regularly posted and identified in
51 accordance with the rules of the Marine Fisheries Commission.
